> Now this would be fine if it weren't for the fact that Objectloader, for some reason, makes it impossible to run Line 47 of UCSCharacter.js, since, for some reason Objectloader doesn't load geometry but a mesh (from what I understand by googling the issue).

There is a short example (not including morph targets) in the [ObjectLoader docs](https://threejs.org/docs/#api/loaders/ObjectLoader). The important thing is that the result is an Object3D or subclass. Adjusting the code from UCSLoader, you might do something like this:

```js
var loader = new THREE.ObjectLoader();
loader.load( config.baseUrl + config.character, function( object ) {
  var geometry;
  object.traverse((node) => {
    if (node.isMesh) geometry = node.geometry;
  });
  // ...
});
```

However, I don't see morph targets in that test file... Can you post the `.blend` file, in case there is a bug in the exporter?

EDIT: Regarding the title, JSONLoader and ObjectLoader load different types of JSON files. The distinction is [explained a little in the docs](https://threejs.org/docs/#api/loaders/ObjectLoader) but generally anything from the Blender exporter will require ObjectLoader, and ObjectLoader supports more features as well.

I don't have the .blend file anymore unfortunately, long story, but I thought I'd figure out if I could get the Morph Targets to work before actually starting to work on the morph targets themselves which would take me a long time. And of course my current json is way too big to be pasted anywhere.

I made this cube to test from now on since it's probably going to be quicker either way https://pastebin.com/Rnh88B2n. 
Here's a link to the blend https://a.pomf.cat/swoqik.blend

I tried out that code you posted. My current Objectloader code looks like this 

```
            var loader = new THREE.ObjectLoader();
		loader.load( config.baseUrl + config.character, function( object ) {
		  var geometry;
		  object.traverse((node) => {
			if (node.isMesh) geometry = node.geometry;
		  });

			geometry.computeBoundingBox();
			geometry.computeVertexNormals();

			mesh = new THREE.SkinnedMesh( geometry, [] );
			mesh.name = config.character;
			scope.root.add( mesh );

			var bb = geometry.boundingBox;
			scope.root.scale.set( config.s, config.s, config.s );
			scope.root.position.set( config.x, config.y - bb.min.y * config.s, config.z );

			mesh.castShadow = true;
			mesh.receiveShadow = true;

			scope.mixer.clipAction( geometry.animations[0], mesh ).play();

			scope.setSkin( 0 );

			scope.checkLoadComplete();
			
		});
```

While it doesn't give me the same errors as before, it seems to have problems with 

```
scope.mixer.clipAction( geometry.animations[0], mesh ).play();
```

As it gives me the error 
```
UCSCharacter.js:61 Uncaught TypeError: Cannot read property '0' of undefined
    at UCSCharacter.js:61
    at ObjectLoader.parse (three.js:34476)
    at Object.onLoad (three.js:34435)
    at XMLHttpRequest.<anonymous> (three.js:30483)
```

If commented out the page seems to load fine, however the cube isn't displayed in any case.

Live test at http://creativiii.com/threejs/examples/webgl_morphtargets_human.html

(apologies for the broken code tag, can't seem to get it working)

This example code you're working from assumes you have a model that uses both morph targets AND skinning, which is greatly overcomplicating this. 🙃

Here is a much simpler example, I would work from that: 

https://morph-test-wnvgoknsdu.now.sh/

The important parts are: 

```js
var loader = new THREE.ObjectLoader();
loader.load( 'test.json', function ( object ) {

  object.traverse((node) => {
    if (node.isMesh) mesh = node;
  });

  mesh.material.morphTargets = true;

  scene.add( mesh );

});
```

```js
function render() {

  if ( mesh ) {
    mesh.rotation.y += 0.01;
    mesh.morphTargetInfluences[0] = (mesh.morphTargetInfluences[0] + 0.01) % 1;
  }

  renderer.render( scene, camera );

}
```

In that case the line `mesh.material.morphTargets = true` needs to be changed:

```js
mesh.traverse((node) => {

  if (!node.isMesh) return;

  var materials = Array.isArray(node.material) ? node.material : [node.material];

  for (var i = 0; i < materials.length; i ++) {
    materials[i].morphTargets = true;
  }

});
```
